'''Bristol board''' (also referred to as '''Bristol paper''') is a heavyweight paper used for [[technical drawing]], [[illustration]], and other two-dimensional art forms. Its bulk thickness is .006 inches or higher. Bristol board is rated by the number of [[ply]]s it contains.

The original bristol board was made in [[Bristol, England]] and was a pasted board made of paper containing rags.

Bristol board provides two working surfaces, front and back.  This quality separates it from illustration board, which only has a front working surface.  The surface texture can vary for different applications, including a smooth plate finish and a medium [[vellum]].  Artists working with friction-based media, such as crayon, chalks, or charcoal would use a rougher texture.  Smooth finishes are generally more suited to other types of media, such as inks.

Bristol paper is also used for [[paperback]] book or catalog covers, file folders, tags, and tickets. Engravers or Wedding bristol paper may be used for formal [[engraved]] wedding invitations.

Bristol board is usually used for school projects. It is sold very cheaply.

